I"M<p>Just like <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/similar-embodiment-predicts-manifold-alignment">similar embodiment</a> and <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/similar-cultural-embedding-predicts-manifold-alignment">cultural embedding</a> do, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/explicit-position-cues-describe-conceptual-structure">explicit</a> words denoting mental states might also predict <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/manifolds-formalize-emergence">manifold</a> alignment. Words like “stress”, “joy”, or “tired” evoke specific <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/triune-brain-model-classifies-brain-regions-through-evolutionary-lens">limbic</a> states <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/context-independent-strategies-are-like-good-chess-moves">in relation to other</a> <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/concept-learning-is-few-shot-scaffolding-supported-by-working-memory">concepts</a>. This hints at the fact that speakers of a certain language think in slightly different, although internally consistent, ways.</p>
